The Future of BCI Application ‚Äì The Mental Sentinel

The world of medicine is one driven by reaction, in which the advancements or measures

to heal people occur only after someone falls ill or shows symptoms of pathology. The fact that

medical professionals seemingly only have the ability to intervene once t he patient is sick

already causes a greater amount of strain on the queue for treatments, and it also leads to a

greater number of people facing illness as a whole. Brain - Computer Interfaces, or BCIs, are

innovative neuroimaging devices which allow a resea rcher/medical practitioner to make a

connection between the neural activity of a patient and a machine which will capture and

visualize the activity for clarity. The incorporation of brain - computer interfaces has allowed

professionals to take a better analysis of patients with neuromuscular disorders such as ALS,

brainstem strokes, and injured spinal cords (Wolpaw et al., 2002). These advancements in

technology have revolutionized the world of neuroimaging, and it is because of these iterations

of technolo gy that better and more effective treatment is possible in the field of medicine. While

these methods of imaging provide useful information through their mechanisms, they are all, as

mentioned above, reactionary measures to look at something abnormal or concerning after the

fact, when it is being used on patients, and this doesn‚Äôt prev ent the patient from avoiding their

condition. The brain is always monitoring the affairs of the internal body, and despite the efforts

of knowing the activity inside, this kn owledge is still inaccessible to medicine, which provides a

major gap in what could be applied to healing people. A future direction for BCI research is BCI

techniques that transcend the realm of medicine , which would be an interface that goes one step

in front of the pathologies that afflict humanity. A BCI that is ten times more advanced than what

exists today is a brain - computer interface that predicts impending illness and pathologies within

a person by analyzing their micro - level changes in the brain‚Äôs activity and structure.

---

3

The BCIs used to analyze the brain in today‚Äôs world are all assistance - based technologies

that help with identifying or following the discrepancies of the brain. The BCI that I am

proposing would no longer serve as a passive tool in the practitioner‚Äôs arse nal; known as the

Mental Sentinel, this BCI would actively scan and detect any minor changes that we cannot

normally see inside the brain, and from there, determine if there are any patterns or concerns

which predict a pathology in that patient‚Äôs future. While a common BCI is searching for ERPs

which occur within someone who already has neuromuscular disease, the Mental Sentinel would

be providing a diagnostic of someone who could have this disorder, and instead of finding out

before it is too late, the BC I would pick up on the patterns and early biomarkers which let the

medical professionals know to have caution proactively, and it is this steadfast work that will

allow the medical field to lower the amount of people facing life altering realities. What th e

Mental Sentinel is specifically looking for are changes seen both within the brain itself, and also

discrepancies seen between the brain and the rest of the body, and these differences are already

aware to the brain and logged, meaning a BCI is a good in novation to tap into the treasure trove

of data that is the human mind. According to Critchley and Harrison (2013), the brain receives

feedback from the afferent visceral signals within the body. It is the nature of the human body‚Äôs

internal signalling sys tem that will pave the way for this new predictive brain - computer

interface.

This brain - computer interface is possible because the mechanisms of the body a re already

in place naturally. The brain is constantly in a state of connection with all of the other organs,

tissues, and systems, such as the respiratory and gastrointestinal systems. It is th is natural feature

of human physiology that will make this predictive technology feasible. The body is constantly

overseeing mechanics such as the hormonal levels, metabolic processes, and immunity at the

---

4

same time. The brain does not wait for something to become an issue before it brings the

difference to its attention and records it; this is the same style of instant data logging that will be

utilized by the Mental Sentinel to view and make accurate judgm ents of what it is detecting in

someone‚Äôs brain. The brain is also capable of picking up on very brief signal changes that are

present right at the beginning of the disease. Some of these signals the brain notices include

changes in cytokine levels, neuroc hemical balance, and alterations in the brain waves as seen

with electroencephalography. Cytokines are produced by the immune cells of the body in

response to infection, which influence the brain to exhibit illness throughout the rest of the body

(Dantzer et al., 2008). These markers of initial disease and illness will serve as supporting data

that can track how accurate the Mental Sentinel is in its predictions, and this can also help make

changes for better predictability. These sets of idle data within t he mind are a wasted opportunity

without the advancements to access them, and with this new BCI, the opportunities to use

biological mechanics in medicine will become broader.

The application of a predictive BCI, like the Mental Sentinel, would require the

technological capability of actively monitoring a patient‚Äôs brain state and archiving this

information into a profile. The Mental Sentinel would then take the stored brain dat a to analyze

what about the patient is abnormal and predictive of certain pathologies, and from there, make

calculations to form a judgment on what needs to be considered, if anything, regarding the

patient. This analysis phase of the BCI would be minimall y invasive, and the actual physical

machinery would operate on the surface of a patient‚Äôs head, using electrodes to electrically

monitor and assess the different regions of the brain. The spatial and temporal resolution of this

interface would also be high in both respects since an assessment of this scale involves many

different variables that the device is searching for, and it will be important that this process

occurs not only efficiently but also accurately, to provide more helpful data. The device would

also be capable of viewing the other aspects of the body from the brain, such as the immune cell

count, available metabolites, and hormone concentrations within the endocrine system. While

maintaining the physical apparatus of an EEG or an fNIR S , the Mental Sentinel will be able to

provide far more intel regarding what is happening in the brain. Once the information has been

accumulated into a patient‚Äôs digital p rofile, the Mental Sentinel would also be assisted with

artificial intelligence to help collate and organize the information to highlight any patterns or

areas of interest and with a well - trained AI model working alongside the BCI, it will enhance the

potential that can be done with the nature of the human body and brain‚Äôs relationship.

There are ethical considerations that need to be considered and addressed with a new

technological advancement like this BCI. The premise of this device involves the accumulation

and documentation of personal neural data of the patients who are treated by it. The whole point

of the Mental Sentinel is to take a deep look into one‚Äôs brain and search for any indication that

something is wrong, such as a potential neural degeneration or disease, and these subjects are

sensitive topics that may leave a patient nervous or uncomfortable logging into a database. The

patient has to understand the potential outcome of being predicted as sick or dying, and they will

need to consent to this knowledge before they are treated. This kind of BCI taps into the realm of

surveillance, which is a hot - button topic in today‚Äôs world, with how companies and corporations

have continuously found methods of injecting surveillance into everything and everybody, and

that area alone is an ethical subject to consider. With all advances in medicine, there is an ethical

concern about the availability of this technology in terms of who can be treated by it and who

can perform research with it. If this helpful tool is only a privilege of the upper - class and

6

researcher institutions with the deepest pockets, this alone is enough to divide the medical world

even further, which is already a considerable issue in today‚Äôs society.

The overall timeline for the application of the Mental Sentinel is split into three points in

time: the immediate application of the device, the later implementation of the device, and the

late - stage system that will be established over a long - term period . The initial phase of

establishing this brain - computer interface into mainstream medicine is to begin accumulating a

store of neural and biological data from patients who are interested in knowing more about their

health and any measures that can be taken to improve it. The intermediate period of the Mental

Sentinel will begin once a sufficient store of useful data is collated and organized into a system.

This collection of data will serve as the basis that the device will use to learn and establish an

understanding of w hat information is standard for the human body and which are aberrant

instances; these discrepancies that it learns will be associated with the appropriate prediction, and

with the assistance of AI, it will establish an algorithm to predict in a given scenario. The late

stage of implementing the Mental Sentinel involves taking the algorithms and rules that it has

learnt in the intermediate period, and from there actually applying its predictive ability to help

inform patients of any measures or considerations they need to have regarding their respective

condition. By this point, the BCI has gone from learning and preparing to predict illnesses to

actually putting in work in the medical field.

The current world of medicine we live in is one that is seemingly never enough. It always

operates in a reactionary way that relies on somebody already being afflicted before treatment is

possible, and that puts a strain on the entire field, not only for the patients, but for the

practitioners as well. The brain - computer interfaces imple mented in the current field are all

designed to be assistive technology rather than up - front treatments. The Mental Sentinel brain -

before they even experience the symptoms of their conditions. This far advancement in the realm
